"Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sherburne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from any of several places called with Old English <i>scīr</i> ‘bright, clear’ + <i>burna</i> ‘stream’, including Sherburn in Elmet (Yorkshire), Sherburn (East Yorkshire, Durham), Shirburn (Oxfordshire), Sherborne (Dorset, Gloucestershire), Sherborne Saint John, Monk Sherborne (Hampshire), Sherbourne (Warwickshire), Sherbourne in Albury (Surrey), and Sherborne in Litton (Somerset). This surname is now rare in Britain."],"variants":[{"name":"Sherburn","meanings":["English: variant of   Sherburne  ."]},{"name":"Sherbon","meanings":["English: variant of   Sherburne   with loss of the second <i>-r-</i> by dissimilation. This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":23,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Sherburne was born about 1359, in Preston, Lancashire, England, her father, Sir Richard Sherburne, was 25 and her mother, Alice Plumpton, was 25. She had at least 1 son with Richard Bayley. She died about 1390, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 33."},"et":{"about 1359–about 1390":"umbes 1359–umbes 1390","1359–1390":"1359–1390","–Female":"Surnud","1358–1391":"1358–1391","1381–1441":"1381–1441","1335–1367":"1335–1367","1335–1408":"1335–1408","about 1390":"umbes 1390","1352":"1352","12 October 1381":"12. oktoober 1381","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","1391":"1391","1390":"1390","1359":"1359","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","1367":"1367","about 1359":"umbes 1359","1441":"1441","1408":"1408","1847":"1847","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England","Stoneyhurst, Clitheroe, Lancashire, England":"Clitheroe, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England, UK":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stonyhurst, Lancashire, England":"Stonyhurst, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"about 1359–about 1390":"noin 1359–noin 1390","1359–1390":"1359–1390","–Female":"Kuollut","1358–1391":"1358–1391","1381–1441":"1381–1441","1335–1367":"1335–1367","1335–1408":"1335–1408","about 1390":"noin 1390","1352":"1352","12 October 1381":"12. lokakuuta 1381","1382":"1382","1381":"1381","1391":"1391","1390":"1390","1359":"1359","1358":"1358","1335":"1335","1367":"1367","about 1359":"noin 1359","1441":"1441","1408":"1408","1847":"1847","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England","Stoneyhurst, Clitheroe, Lancashire, England":"Clitheroe, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lancashire, England, UK":"Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Stonyhurst, Lancashire, England":"Stonyhurst, Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"about 1359–about 13